the president's comments today
and earlier and the implications

03:04.400 --> 03:06.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of what he says publicly,
we turn to Matthew Dowd.

03:06.400 --> 03:10.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's the former chief strategist
for President George W. Bush
in 2004 and author of "A New

03:12.366 --> 03:15.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Way: Embracing the Paradox
as We Lead and Serve."

03:15.800 --> 03:20.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Beverly Gage, she's
professor of American
history at Yale University.

03:20.133 --> 03:22.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome both of you
back to the "NewsHour."

03:22.966 --> 03:25.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Matt Dowd, I'm going
to start with you.

03:25.300 --> 03:30.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We know we have seen
politicians get into some
tough language over the years.

03:32.233 --> 03:35.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How does what we heard from
President Trump today on
Twitter fit into all of that?

03:35.166 --> 03:38.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MATTHEW DOWD, Former Bush
Campaign Strategist: Well, we
have come a long way from when I

03:38.933 --> 03:42.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
worked for George W. Bush in
2000, when he pledged to bring
honor and dignity back to

03:42.800 --> 03:46.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Oval Office and won as that
as being part of his platform.

03:46.100 --> 03:48.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Judy, I think this
is a bigger problem.

03:48.233 --> 03:51.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
First, as you know, in this
democracy, in order to have
a healthy democracy, we have

03:51.833 --> 03:53.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to get to the common good.

03:53.900 --> 03:56.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the only way to get to
the common good is if we have
a common set of facts, which

03:56.966 --> 04:00.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
we don't seem to have
today, and we have a
common level of decency.

04:00.266 --> 04:04.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And my problem with the
president and what happened
today and why I think it affects

04:04.166 --> 04:07.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the country as a whole
is, first, we bring up
our kids better than this.

04:07.466 --> 04:09.433 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We teach them not to do this.

04:09.433 --> 04:11.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We tell them not to do
this, and it is not the
right standard of behavior.

04:11.933 --> 04:15.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But for a president -- secondly,
but, for a president, he
sets the pattern of behavior

04:15.966 --> 04:20.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for the entire country and what
we can expect for how we each
other act and how we should

04:20.266 --> 04:22.333 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be in politics.

04:22.333 --> 04:26.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And, third, just from
a practical aspect of
it, just totally looking
at it pragmatically,

04:28.300 --> 04:30.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his behavior in this, in the
midst of what he is trying
to do on health care and the

04:30.566 --> 04:33.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
votes he is trying to get, is
incredibly counterproductive.

04:33.366 --> 04:37.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, from all of those avenues,
one from a history of our
democracy that is dependent

04:37.700 --> 04:41.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
on a level of decency
that doesn't seem to
be apparent here, but,
two, just practically,

04:41.766 --> 04:44.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
if he wants to get something
done, this makes it harder.

04:44.333 --> 04:46.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, I
want to ask you about that
latter part in a moment.

04:46.933 --> 04:51.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, Beverly Gage, how does what
this president is saying when
these kinds of tweets go out,

04:53.866 --> 04:57.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how does it compare from
what we have heard from
other presidents over time?

04:57.000 --> 05:01.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BEVERLY GAGE, Yale University:
Unfortunately, I don't think
that American presidents have

05:01.100 --> 05:06.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
always lived up to the standard
of decency that we have
tended to expect of them, but

05:08.100 --> 05:11.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think presidents before Trump,
when those moments happened,
they tended to be the exception,

05:11.866 --> 05:13.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
rather than the rule.

05:13.966 --> 05:17.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So there was a famous moment
in 1950 when Harry Truman was
president, and a music critic

05:19.500 --> 05:24.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
wrote a very critical piece
about Truman's daughter, who had
just given a singing recital.

05:26.133 --> 05:29.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Truman fired off this
ferocious letter threatening to
punch the guy out, and telling

05:29.633 --> 05:33.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
him that he was a gutter
snipe and an idiot and he was
going to kick him in the nuts.

05:33.100 --> 05:34.333 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

05:34.333 --> 05:36.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, it was pretty
aggressive language.

05:36.366 --> 05:40.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there was a big reaction to
that at the time, a president
kind of attacking a private

05:41.266 --> 05:42.533 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
citizen.

05:42.533 --> 05:44.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Many people thought
it wasn't dignified.

05:44.633 --> 05:48.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But nobody would have said
that this is Harry Truman's
mode of being all the time.

05:48.700 --> 05:53.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was seen as a kind
of authentic moment of
outrage, and not a kind
of permanent presidential

05:54.533 --> 05:57.066 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
style.

05:57.066 --> 05:59.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Matt
Dowd, is there a level
of dignity that Americans
expect from a president?

05:59.566 --> 06:04.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
